[2] South Korea: 11 947 confirmed cases, 276 deaths
Date: Thu 11 Jun 2020
Source: Ministry of Health and Welfare, Korean CDC [in English, abridged, edited]
http://ncov.mohw.go.kr/en/bdBoardList.do?brdId=16&brdGubun=162&dataGubun=&ncvContSeq=&contSeq=&board_id=


[Please note that while the data goes through 00:00 11 Jun 2020, in actuality, it covers all newly reported cases and deaths occurring on 10 Jun 2020. - Mod.UBA]

10 Jun 2020 0:00 AM KT 11 902 confirmed cases, 276 deaths
11 Jun 2020 0:00 AM KT 11 947 confirmed cases, 276 deaths
Change: 45 newly confirmed infections; 0 new deaths

[The table with distribution by provinces is available at the source URL above. - Mod.UBA]

The English language page, notice 368 (https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=&bid=0030), provides updates on clusters as of today (11 Jun 2020):

- Coupang logistics center cluster in Bucheon-si, Gyeonggi Province: 2 additional cases were confirmed from testing for release from self-quarantine. In total, 146 cases have been confirmed.
- The newly planted churches in the Seoul Metropolitan Region: 2 additional cases were confirmed. In total, 94 cases have been confirmed.
- Richway in Gwangak-gu, Seoul: 116 cases have been confirmed in total to date. Epidemiological investigation revealed that a case confirmed on 3 Jun [2020] related to Jesus Malsseum Silcheon Church had visited Richway on 21 May [2020]. The 9 cases related to Jesus Malsseum Silcheon Church have been reclassified and are now included in the Richway cluster.
- The sport facility in Yangcheon-gu, Seoul: 6 additional cases were confirmed. The new cases are contacts of visitor(s) to the table tennis facility. In total, 60 cases have been confirmed.
- Defense Security Support Command in Gwacheon-si, Gyeonggi Province: 2 additional cases were confirmed. The new cases are family members of confirmed case(s). In total, 7 cases have been confirmed.
- Korea National Institute of Health will distribute COVID-19-positive respiratory specimens to support development of diagnostic devices for COVID-19 and COVID-19-related research.
- KCDC has collected about 1700 leftover COVID-19-positive respiratory specimens from testing laboratories and medical institutions. KNIH will distribute them through application and review process.
- Since COVID-19 symptoms are often mild and non-specific, many infected persons go unnoticed and are confirmed after having already transmitted onward to other people. KCDC advises high precaution.
- Since COVID-19 outbreak can occur from any venue under crowded, confined, and close-contact environment, residents of the Seoul Metropolitan Region are advised to avoid club meetings, religious small group meetings, and other gatherings taking place in poorly ventilated enclosed areas and to practice handwashing, mask wearing, and physical distancing in daily life.
- Anyone who has come in close contact with a large number of unspecified persons is advised to dial 1339 or contact a local public health center and get tested at a screening clinic if fever or respiratory symptoms appear.
- Testing is advised especially if 2 or more people in a household or a social group with recent physical contact develop symptoms.
- Recently, daytime temperature is frequently rising above 30 deg C [86 deg F]. People aged 65 or older and people with chronic medical condition are not only COVID-19 high-risk groups but also vulnerable to falling ill from heat waves. People belonging to such groups are advised to avoid going outside during daytime where there is high chance of exposure to other people and temperature is high.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the past 24 hours, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 45 cases and no new deaths, compared with 50 cases and 2 deaths the previous day (9 Jun 2020). The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 65 consecutive days. Today's (10 Jun 2020) breakdown of cases: 40 cases were locally transmitted, and 5 were imported cases. Locally acquired cases were in Seoul (20), Gyeonggi (15), and Incheon (5). Imported cases were 2 in Quarantine and 1 each in Seoul, Gyeonggi, and Incheon. Note that 14 provinces did not report any newly confirmed cases.

The detailed discussions of the clusters following the opening up of venues clearly illustrates the increased risk of transmission in enclosed, indoor venues with high density, including houses of worship. The clusters keep growing and expanding in geographic location. One wonders if other heightened measures might be implemented to slow down the transmission.

The impression (hasn't changed): Lifting of measures has been accompanied by increases in locally acquired infections through increasing clusters related to gatherings of people at employment (bringing it outside employment to contacts) and in houses of worship as well as bars and clubs. It just takes one super spreader in a crowded place to transmit and lead to a sizeable cluster.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7459205,195. - Mod.UBA]

