[3] Italy: 236 142 total cases, 34 167 deaths
Date: Thu 11 Jun 2020
Source: Italian Government Health Ministry [in Italian, machine trans., edited]
http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioNotizieNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&menu=notizie&p=dalministero&id=4881


The increase in new cases of COVID-19 is 379 against 202 yesterday [10 Jun 2020]. This is what can be seen from the health monitoring data on the spread of the new coronavirus [SARS-CoV-2] released at 18:00 CET on [11 Jun 2020].

- 236 142 cumulative cases, an increase of 202 from 9 Jun 2020;
- 30 637 people are currently positive for the virus;
- 171 338 people have recovered;
- 4131 patients are hospitalized with symptoms, 236 are in intensive care, and 26 270 are in home isolation;
- 34 167 deaths have been reported; however, this number can be confirmed only after the Istituto Superiore di Sanita has established the actual cause of death.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Italy is now 236 142 cases, including 34 167 deaths, up by 379 cases and 53 deaths in the past 24 hours. The previous day's (10 Jun 2020) 24-hour change was 202 cases and 71 deaths. The numbers of hospitalized cases and cases in the ICU are still in decline. As it has been, the major increase in cases was in Lombardy, reporting 252 newly confirmed cases.

Cases still continue to be concentrated in Lombardy, the original epicenter of the outbreak, Emilia-Romagna, Lazio, Piedmont, Tuscany, and Liguria (see tables at http://www.salute.gov.it/imgs/C_17_notizie_4881_0_file.pdf). These 6 provinces combined today (11 Jun 2020) account for 94.7% of reported newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Lombardy again reported the largest number of newly confirmed cases in the 24-hour period (252) and was the only province reporting more than 50 new cases. Also, 15 provinces reported fewer than 10 newly confirmed cases, and of these, 4 provinces reported no new cases, all signs of decreasing local transmission.

The top 5 provinces by cumulative case count remain unchanged and are Lombardy, followed by Piedmont, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto, and Tuscany. The top 6 provinces by number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours are Lombardy (252), followed by Piedmont (42), Emilia-Romagna (25), Lazio (20), and Liguria and Tuscany (10 each).

Italy is now 37 days post phase 2 initial opening up and 21 days post 2nd stage of phase 2 opening up.

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7459205,75. - Mod.UBA]

******
[4] Iran: 177 938 total cases, 8506 deaths
Date: Thu 11 Jun 2020
Source: BBC [ edited]
https://www.bbc.com/news/52959756


Iran has seen a rapid surge in the numbers of coronavirus cases in recent weeks, sparking fears it might be facing a 2nd wave of the pandemic.

Iran started to relax its lockdown in mid-April [2020], after the number of infections declined, so is it paying the price? New infections have been averaging more than 3000 a day in the 1st week of June, a 50% increase on the previous week.

The figure reached a high of 3574, on Thu 4 Jun [2020], before dropping slightly.
The previous highest figure was 3186, on 30 Mar [2020], during the initial outbreak, when Iran became one of the worst-affected countries outside China.

At that time, the Iranian authorities were criticised for their hesitation in closing down mosques and key religious sites in the city of Qom and for not moving quicker to restrict movement. Then, in April [2020], as the number of new cases dropped to below 1000 a day, Iran began to ease its lockdown restrictions:
- 20 Apr: Shopping malls and bazaars reopen, and travel resumes between different provinces
- 22 Apr: public parks and recreation areas reopen
- 12 May: government says all mosques can reopen
- 25 May: major Shia religious shrines reopen
- 26 May: restaurants, cafes, museums, and historical sites reopen
And city transport systems across Iran, as well as banks and offices, have been packed with people.

The epidemic was initially concentrated in Qom and the capital, Tehran. But now, a flare-up has been reported in the southwest, notably in Khuzestan province, an oil-rich region that borders Iraq.

There is clearly more social interaction with the easing of restrictions, but officials have suggested the surge in new cases could be down to more testing. President Hassan Rouhani has said this means you will find more cases.

Iran's chief epidemiologist at the country's health ministry, Mohammad-Mehdi Gouya, explained: "The main reason for the rising numbers is that we have started identifying [infected people] who have no or mild symptoms."

It currently does one test for every 79 people, which is up from about one test for every 380 2 months ago. However, when you look at the proportion of these tests that are positive, there is a clear upward trend since the middle and end of May after it dropped sharply in April [2020]. On 29 May [2020], just under 11% of tests were positive, but by 6 Jun [2020], that figure had risen to over 14%.

Health officials have also pointed out the number of daily deaths recorded have remained below 100 since mid-April -2020]. It has been between 30 and 90 for the past month. But it would take several weeks after the initial rise in infections for an increase in recorded deaths to become apparent. And a report by the Iranian parliament's research centre, in April [2020], suggested the real death toll could be twice as high as the official number, which comprises deaths in hospitals only.

Health Minister Saeed Namaki said people were ignoring social-distancing rules. "People have become completely careless regarding this disease," he told the Iranian news agency. "If our people fail to respect the health protocols... we must prepare ourselves for the worst situation."

A health ministry poll last week suggested only:
- 40% of the population are keeping the social-distancing rules, down from 90% earlier in the outbreak; and
- 32% are following the rules on self-isolation, down from 86%.

President Hassan Rouhani has warned restrictions may have to be reintroduced if the outbreak worsens.

"To contain the virus, you need a lockdown," says Rana Rahimpour, "and in a lockdown, you need to be able to pay people."

[Byline: Zulfiqar Ali]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As of 10 Jun 2020, the total number of cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Iran is 177 938, including 8506 deaths, an increase of 2011 new cases and 81 deaths since 10 Jun 2020. Iran has started relaxing restrictions on a more widespread basis in the country. With the increasing daily case reports having surpassed the prior peak in late March-early April 2020, it is clear that there is now a 2nd wave, most likely due to too early lifting of restrictions. The key concern will be whether people begin travelling again within the country and may transport the virus from one zone to another.

A map of Iran showing provinces can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/iran/iran-political-map.html and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7459205,128. - Mod.MPP]

