[The above are the latest breakdowns of confirmed cases of SARS-CoV-2 infection in the USA as per Worldometer data. The total number of confirmed cases in the USA and territories is now 2 066 401, including 115 130 deaths, an increase from 2 045 549 cases and 114 148 deaths in the past 24 hours. New York City had a cumulative total of 205 405 as of 12:45 EDT (GMT-4) on 11 Jun 2020 (an increase of 829 newly confirmed cases since 10 Jun 2020, up from 323 on 9 Jun 2020) including 17 300 confirmed deaths (an increase of 97 deaths since 10 Jun 2020 and up from 34 deaths on 9 Jun 2020) and an additional 4693 probable deaths (https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page).

The top 10 states in terms of daily reported cases in descending order are California, Texas, Arizona, Florida, North Carolina, Georgia, New York, Illinois, Alabama, and Maryland. A number of these states do not have many large urban centers, and the increase in case numbers is consistent with media reports that transmission is now occurring in smaller communities that had not had many cases during the past few months and many of these communities did not practice social distancing or use face masks to slow down transmission.

In terms of cumulative case reports, New York is number one, followed by New Jersey, California, Illinois, Massachusetts, Texas, Pennsylvania, Florida, Michigan, and Maryland, the same 10 states as yesterday (10 Jun 2020) but in different order. A total of 38 states and entities have reported more than 10 000 cumulative cases each.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention website (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html) has a growth curve and a table giving demographics (age and ethnicity) when known.

A map of the United States can be seen at http://www.mapsofworld.com/usa/ and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7459205,106. - Mod.UBA]
